Simplifying further, it turns out we don't actually need to try to resolve anything to demonstrate this issue; just getting a resolver will do the trick:

```java
while (true) {
    final RoundRobinDnsAddressResolverGroup resolverGroup =
            new RoundRobinDnsAddressResolverGroup(NioDatagramChannel.class,
                    DefaultDnsServerAddressStreamProvider.INSTANCE);

    // UDP ports don't get opened unless we actually try to get a resolver;
    // in the real use case, this happens by way of bootstrap.connect(), but
    // I've opted to use this as a more concise example. I definitely recognize
    // the possibility that there may be nuanced differences between the real
    // use case and this minimal example, but hope it gets the point across.
    resolverGroup.getResolver(eventLoopGroup.next());

    // In a vacuum, I would expect any ports opened by the resolver to be closed
    // by this statement, but they appear to remain open even after the resolver
    // group is closed.
    resolverGroup.close();

    Thread.sleep(1000);
}
```
